<td valign="top">
<p><img height="185" width="300" src="http://www.edenhrconsulting.com/images/stories/eden-stick-figures/eden-recruit.jpg" alt="eden-recruit" style="float: right;" />Firstly a word of warning; compromise agreements are not the panacea to all employment ills. They need to be used with caution and only in appropriate circumstances.</p>
<p>Ever since a notable legal case, BNP Paribas v Mezzoterro [2004], compromise agreements have been subject to a considerable amount of scrutiny and they do not excuse an Organisation of its responsibilities for dealing with employment related issues within the relevant legislative frameworks.</p>
<p>In certain circumstances, compromise agreements provide a good deal of security for both parties, but there principle use is for when a serious issue has been identified and the employer/ employee relationship has broken down irrevocably, in which case, compromise agreements are the ideal tool for resolution.</p>
<p>Eden HR can advise you on the nuances of compromise agreements, draft an agreement for you, negotiate impartially with employees, and deal with solicitors on your behalf.</p>
<p> </p></td>
